Package com.telenav.kivakit.core.value.count

Class Count

java.lang.Object
com.telenav.kivakit.core.value.count.BaseCount<Count>
com.telenav.kivakit.core.value.count.Count
All Implemented Interfaces:
Countable, NextIterator<Count>, Mapper<Long,Count>, Arithmetic<Count>, Maximizable<Count>, Minimizable<Count>, Numeric<Count>, Zeroable, AsString, StringFormattable, DoubleValued, FormattedLongValued, LongValued, Source<Long>, Comparable<Countable>, Supplier<Long>
public class Count extends BaseCount<Count>
Represents a count of something.

Counts have useful properties that primitive values like long and int do not have:

  1. Counts are guaranteed to be positive values, so it is not possible to have a Count of -1
  2. Counts have a variety of useful and convenient methods for:
    • Conversion
    • Comparison
    • Mathematics
    • Looping
    • Iteration
    • Array allocation
  3. Counts implement the LongValued interface, which makes them interoperable with methods that consume LongValued objects.
  4. Counts provide a more readable, comma-separated String representation by default

Efficiency

Count objects are cheaper than they might seem for two reasons:

  • (1) low count constants and powers of two can be accessed as constant objects (like _1024 or _15) and values up to 65,536 are cached so that no new object is created if you call count(long)
  • (2) allocation of count objects higher than 65,536 are cheap in Java due to the design of generational garbage collectors. This said, there will be occasions where Count objects are not desirable (for example, inside a doubly nested loop) and sometimes they may improve a public API method or constructor, while the internal representation is a primitive value for efficiency.

Although Count objects are convenient and make method signatures clear and type-safe, as always, the best approach is to simply use Count objects until a clear inefficiency shows up in a profiler like YourKit.

Creation

  • count(long) - Returns the given long as a Count
  • count(double) - Casts the given double to a long and returns that as a Count
  • count(Object[]) - Returns the Count of slots in the array
  • count(Iterable) - Returns the Count of items provided by the given Iterable
  • count(Iterator) - Returns the Count of items provided the given Iterator
  • count(Collection) - Returns the Count of items in the given Collection

Conversion

  • BaseCount.longValue() - This count as a long value
  • BaseCount.asInt() - This count cast to an int value
  • LongValued.asLong() - This count as a long
  • BaseCount.get() - This count as a long
  • BaseCount.count() - This count
  • BaseCount.asBitCount() - This count as a BitCount
  • BaseCount.asEstimate() - This count as an Estimate
  • BaseCount.asMaximum() - This count as a Maximum
  • BaseCount.asMinimum() - This count as a Minimum

String Representations

  • FormattedLongValued.asString(Format) - This count formatted in the given format
  • FormattedLongValued.asCommaSeparatedString() - This count as a comma-separated string, like 65,536
  • FormattedLongValued.asSimpleString() ()} - This count as a simple string, like 65536

Comparison

  • BaseCount.compareTo(Countable) - Comparable.compareTo(Object) implementation
  • LongValued.isLessThan(LongValued) - True if this count is less than the given quantum
  • LongValued.isGreaterThan(LongValued) - True if this count is greater than the given quantum
  • LongValued.isLessThanOrEqualTo(LongValued) - True if this count is less than or equal to the given quantum
  • - True if this count is greater than or equal to the given quantum
  • BaseCount.isZero() - True if this count is zero
  • Zeroable.isNonZero() - True if this count is not zero

Minima and Maxima

  • MAXIMUM - The largest count possible
  • MAXIMUM_BYTE_VALUE - Byte.MAX_VALUE
  • MAXIMUM_CHARACTER_VALUE - Character.MAX_VALUE
  • MAXIMUM_SHORT_VALUE - Short.MAX_VALUE
  • MAXIMUM_INTEGER_VALUE - Integer.MAX_VALUE
  • MAXIMUM_LONG_VALUE - Long.MAX_VALUE
  • BaseCount.isMaximum() - True if this count is MAXIMUM
  • BaseCount.isMinimum() - True if this count is zero
  • BaseCount.asMaximum() - Converts this count to a Maximum
  • BaseCount.asMinimum() - Converts this count to a Minimum

Arithmetic

  • BaseCount.decremented() - This count minus one
  • BaseCount.incremented() - This count plus one
  • BaseCount.plus(LongValued) - This count plus the given count
  • BaseCount.plus(long) - This count plus the given value
  • BaseCount.minus(LongValued) - This count minus the given count
  • BaseCount.minus(long) - This count minus the given value
  • BaseCount.dividedBy(LongValued) - This count divided by the given count, using integer division without rounding
  • BaseCount.dividedBy(long) - This count divided by the given value, using integer division without rounding
  • BaseCount.times(LongValued) - This count times the given count
  • BaseCount.times(long) - This count times the given value
  • BaseCount.times(double) - This count times the given value, cast to a long value
  • BaseCount.times(Percent) - This count times the given percentage

Mathematics

  • BaseCount.percent(Percent) - The given percentage of this count
  • BaseCount.percentOf(LongValued) - This count as a percentage of the given count
  • BaseCount.dividesEvenlyBy(LongValued) - True if there is no remainder when dividing this count by the given count
  • BaseCount.powerOfTenCeiling(int) - The maximum value of this count taking on the given number of digits
  • BaseCount.powerOfTenFloor(int) - The minimum value of this count taking on the given number of digits
  • BaseCount.asPrimeAllocationSize() - The next prime value from a limited table of primes, useful in allocating linear hashmaps
  • BaseCount.bitsToRepresent() - The number of bits required to represent this count
  • BaseCount.powerOfTwoCeiling() - The next power of two above this count

Looping

  • BaseCount.loop(Runnable) - Runs the given code block BaseCount.count() times

Iteration

  • BaseCount.forEachByte(Consumer) - Passes to the given consumer, each byte from 0 to the smaller of this count or MAXIMUM_BYTE_VALUE, exclusive
  • BaseCount.forEachInteger(Consumer) - Passes to the given consumer, each byte from 0 to the smaller of this count or MAXIMUM_INTEGER_VALUE, exclusive
  • BaseCount.forEachLong(Consumer) - Passes each long from 0 to LongValued.asLong() to the given consumer, exclusive
  • BaseCount.forEachShort(Consumer) - Passes to the given consumer, each byte from 0 to the smaller of this count or MAXIMUM_SHORT_VALUE, exclusive

Array Allocation

  • BaseCount.newByteArray() - Allocates a byte array of BaseCount.count() elements
  • BaseCount.newCharArray() - Allocates a char array of BaseCount.count() elements
  • BaseCount.newDoubleArray() - Allocates a double array of BaseCount.count() elements
  • BaseCount.newFloatArray() - Allocates a float array of BaseCount.count() elements
  • BaseCount.newIntArray() - Allocates an int array of BaseCount.count() elements
  • BaseCount.newLongArray() - Allocates a long array of BaseCount.count() elements
  • BaseCount.newObjectArray() - Allocates an Object array of BaseCount.count() elements
  • BaseCount.newShortArray() - Allocates a short array of BaseCount.count() elements
  • BaseCount.newStringArray() - Allocates a String array of BaseCount.count() elements

Count objects implement the BaseCount.hashCode() / BaseCount.equals(Object) contract and are Comparable.
